<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="type material">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Type material.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Holotype, examined for 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.423.7536" author="Brunke, A" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 113" refId="B2" refString="Brunke, A, Solodovnikov, A, 2014. A revision of the Neotropical species of Bolitogyrus Chevrolat, a geographically disjunct lineage of Staphylinini (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). ZooKeys 423: 1 - 113, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.423.7536" title="A revision of the Neotropical species of Bolitogyrus Chevrolat, a geographically disjunct lineage of Staphylinini (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.423.7536" volume="423" year="2014">Brunke and Solodovnikov (2014)</bibRefCitation>
, images used for comparison.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Within the Strigifrons group (for diagnosis, see 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.423.7536" author="Brunke, A" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 113" refId="B2" refString="Brunke, A, Solodovnikov, A, 2014. A revision of the Neotropical species of Bolitogyrus Chevrolat, a geographically disjunct lineage of Staphylinini (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). ZooKeys 423: 1 - 113, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.423.7536" title="A revision of the Neotropical species of Bolitogyrus Chevrolat, a geographically disjunct lineage of Staphylinini (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.423.7536" volume="423" year="2014">Brunke and Solodovnikov (2014)</bibRefCitation>
): strigulose sculpture of elytra present and more expansive, not restricted to small lateral patch; posterior protuberances of head not creating expansive impunctate areas; abdominal tergites VI-VII with disc impunctate medially. 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", sensu nov." baseAuthorityName="Wendeler" baseAuthorityYear="1928" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Bolitogyrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bolitogyrus strigifrons" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strigifrons">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Bolitogyrus strigifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName family="Staphylinidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. pseudostrigifrons" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="pseudostrigifrons">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. pseudostrigifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can be easily recognized externally by the impunctate medial area on tergite VII and the more expansive strigulose sculpture on the elytra. The paramere is also markedly different (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Male genitalia A, C, E Bolitogyrus strigifrons (Wendeler) B, D, F B. pseudostrigifrons Brunke G, I B. nigropolitus Smetana H, J B. nigropolitoides A, B, G, H median lobe in lateral and C, D ventral view. E, F, I, J inner face of paramere, apex. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A-D, G, H); 0.1 mm (E, F, I, J)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1096.80773.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672696" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2E</figureCitation>
), with the overall shape evenly narrowed to the apex and with simple, organized marginal rows of peg setae; it is also longer than the median lobe. Additionally, the median lobe in ventral view is more strongly convergent to a narrower apex (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Male genitalia A, C, E Bolitogyrus strigifrons (Wendeler) B, D, F B. pseudostrigifrons Brunke G, I B. nigropolitus Smetana H, J B. nigropolitoides A, B, G, H median lobe in lateral and C, D ventral view. E, F, I, J inner face of paramere, apex. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A-D, G, H); 0.1 mm (E, F, I, J)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1096.80773.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672696" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2C</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
In its revised sense, 
<taxonomicName family="Staphylinidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. strigifrons" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="strigifrons">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. strigifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the holotype male, collected from an imprecise locality in Veracruz state, Mexico (
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Jalapa”">&quot;Jalapa&quot;</normalizedToken>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
At the moment, sister species 
<taxonomicName family="Staphylinidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. pseudostrigifrons" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="pseudostrigifrons">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. pseudostrigifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Hidalgo) and 
<taxonomicName family="Staphylinidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. strigifrons" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="strigifrons">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. strigifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Veracruz) appear to be broadly allopatric but more collecting is needed in Veracruz and Puebla states at medium elevations to verify this.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
